id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM0
label: ESTJc
text:
Translator: Queenie Lee
Reviewer: Ivana Korom

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM1
label: ESTJc
text: Let me ask you something.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM2
label: ESTJc
text: Have you ever been in a situation

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM3
label: ESTJc
text:
where you've asked yourself
the following question:

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM4
label: ESTJc
text:
is this person, is this person
flirting with me?

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM5
label: ESTJc
text:
Picture the scene:
you're at a friend's party.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM6
label: ESTJc
text: You sashay into the kitchen

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM7
label: ESTJc
text:
because we all know
that's where the fun is.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM8
label: ESTJc
text: And you see an attractive stranger

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM9
label: ESTJc
text: getting a drink refill from a box of wine.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM10
label: ESTJc
text: Your friend's a student.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM11
label: ESTJc
text: And so you get a drink refill,

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM12
label: ESTJc
text:
and you say something hilarious
to the attractive stranger.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM13
label: ESTJc
text: Attractive stranger laughs.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM14
label: ESTJc
text: Good for you.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM15
label: ESTJc
text: And then for the next few minutes

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM16
label: ESTJc
text: there's some eye contact, more talking.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM17
label: ESTJc
text: But then after a few minutes

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM18
label: ESTJc
text:
you start thinking,
'Is this person flirting with me?'

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM19
label: ESTJc
text: Sound familiar, anyone?

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM20
label: ESTJc
text:
See the person sitting next to you,
it's happened to them.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM21
label: ESTJc
text:
The person in front of you,
it's happened to them.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM22
label: ESTJc
text: You see this is a universal conundrum.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM23
label: ESTJc
text: But no more!

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM24
label: ESTJc
text: Because in the next ten minutes

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM25
label: ESTJc
text:
I'm going to tell you
the signs of flirting

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM26
label: ESTJc
text:
and never again will you wonder:
is this person flirting with me?

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM27
label: ESTJc
text: I'm Jean Smith.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM28
label: ESTJc
text:
I'm a social anthropologist
who studies flirting,

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM29
label: ESTJc
text: a flirtologist, if you will.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM30
label: ESTJc
text:
Now, as a flirtologist, I do research,
I write books, I give talks.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM31
label: ESTJc
text:
And I work with clients
both private and corporate,

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM32
label: ESTJc
text:
all with the goal of helping people
to become better flirts.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM33
label: ESTJc
text:
So I can see some of you
sitting there, you're thinking,

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM34
label: ESTJc
text:
'Really!? Is this necessary?
I mean teaching people how to flirt?'

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM35
label: ESTJc
text: Yes.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM36
label: ESTJc
text: (Laughter)

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM37
label: ESTJc
text: Yes, it is.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM38
label: ESTJc
text: I've been doing this for over a decade.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM39
label: ESTJc
text: And if the question -

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM40
label: ESTJc
text:
is this person flirting with me -
was popular then,

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM41
label: ESTJc
text:
it's now everyone-wants-
to-take-it-to-prom popular

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM42
label: ESTJc
text: because over the last decade

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM43
label: ESTJc
text:
the way that we flirt
has changed dramatically.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM44
label: ESTJc
text:
People are relying more and more
on digital ways of communicating.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM45
label: ESTJc
text: But let's face it,

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM46
label: ESTJc
text: an emoji with its tongue sticking out,

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM47
label: ESTJc
text: it's only going to get you so far.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM48
label: ESTJc
text:
At some point, you're going
to have to meet in person.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM49
label: ESTJc
text: Unless of course, you're a Japanese male,

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM50
label: ESTJc
text:
and in that case, you could go on to marry
your video game girlfriend: Rinko.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM51
label: ESTJc
text:
So as part of my quest
to help people become better flirts,

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM52
label: ESTJc
text: I did research.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM53
label: ESTJc
text:
I went to the cities of London,
New York, Paris and Stockholm,

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM54
label: ESTJc
text:
and I researched the flirting behaviour
of its inhabitants.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM55
label: ESTJc
text:
And I found there were six things
that they all had in common.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM56
label: ESTJc
text:
Six ways that they could signal
they were flirting

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM57
label: ESTJc
text:
and understood when someone
was flirting with them.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM58
label: ESTJc
text: And I teach this as

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM59
label: ESTJc
text: H.O.T.-A.P.E.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM60
label: ESTJc
text: (Laughter)

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM61
label: ESTJc
text:
It's the six signs - it's an acronym
for the six signs of flirting.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM62
label: ESTJc
text:
So what if I were to say to you:
'You must be a parking ticket

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM63
label: ESTJc
text:
because you've got "fine"
written all over you.'

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM64
label: ESTJc
text: Would you laugh?

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM65
label: ESTJc
text: Well, 'H' is for humour.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM66
label: ESTJc
text:
Raise your hand
if you thought my joke was funny.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM67
label: ESTJc
text: Go ahead, don't be shy.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM68
label: ESTJc
text: OK, everyone with their hands up,

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM69
label: ESTJc
text: I would totally date you.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM70
label: ESTJc
text: (Laughter)

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM71
label: ESTJc
text:
Well, if my husband
weren't such a control freak.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM72
label: ESTJc
text:
But anyway, if you
didn't raise your hands,

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM73
label: ESTJc
text: it's not a good match.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM74
label: ESTJc
text: It's just not going to work between us.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM75
label: ESTJc
text: But it's me, not you.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM76
label: ESTJc
text: But this is a good thing

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM77
label: ESTJc
text: because HOTAPE-ing people -

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM78
label: ESTJc
text: it takes time.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM79
label: ESTJc
text:
Does anyone here
like reading a good novel,

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM80
label: ESTJc
text: watching an interesting TED talk?

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM81
label: ESTJc
text: Does anyone here like test cricket?

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM82
label: ESTJc
text:
These things also take time,
especially test cricket, five days?

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM83
label: ESTJc
text:
And this is where people
often get it wrong

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM84
label: ESTJc
text: because they want to attract everybody.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM85
label: ESTJc
text:
But no, you just want
to attract those people

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM86
label: ESTJc
text: who match with you.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM87
label: ESTJc
text: And that's why humour,

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM88
label: ESTJc
text: specifically a shared sense of humour,

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM89
label: ESTJc
text:
is really important
for helping you to differentiate

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM90
label: ESTJc
text:
between your potential HOT-APEs
and squirrel monkeys.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM91
label: ESTJc
text: I mean, yeah, they're cute.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM92
label: ESTJc
text: I'm sure they have a great personality.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM93
label: ESTJc
text:
But at the end of the day
it's a squirrel monkey.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM94
label: ESTJc
text: It's no HOT-APE.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM95
label: ESTJc
text: So 'O' is for open body language.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM96
label: ESTJc
text: Three things to remember.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM97
label: ESTJc
text: Number one, don't do this.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM98
label: ESTJc
text: I know some of you are guilty of this.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM99
label: ESTJc
text: I've heard it all before,

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM100
label: ESTJc
text: oh, but I'm cold, or, this is comfortable.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM101
label: ESTJc
text: OK, whiny voice aside, in which instance

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM102
label: ESTJc
text: do you want to HOT-APE me more?

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM103
label: ESTJc
text: Like this?

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM104
label: ESTJc
text: Or like this, right?

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM105
label: ESTJc
text: Not HOT-APE.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM106
label: ESTJc
text: HOT-APE.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM107
label: ESTJc
text:
Number two: make sure your shoulders
are facing the person.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM108
label: ESTJc
text: So not HOT-APE,

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM109
label: ESTJc
text: not HOT-APE, still not HOT-APE.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM110
label: ESTJc
text: HOT-APE.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM111
label: ESTJc
text: Not HOT-APE.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM112
label: ESTJc
text: HOT-APE.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM113
label: ESTJc
text:
Now, the third,
this is the most important,

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM114
label: ESTJc
text: and I'm only telling you guys.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM115
label: ESTJc
text: This is a really good one.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM116
label: ESTJc
text: To see if someone's interested,

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM117
label: ESTJc
text:
look at the direction
in which their feet are pointing.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM118
label: ESTJc
text:
So if their feet
are pointing at you, a good sign.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM119
label: ESTJc
text: If they're kind of out to the side,

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM120
label: ESTJc
text:
it means they're planning
their escape route.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM121
label: ESTJc
text:
The further away our limbs
are from our brain,

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM122
label: ESTJc
text: the harder it is for us to control them.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM123
label: ESTJc
text:
So, Shakira, I know you say:
the hips don't lie,

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM124
label: ESTJc
text:
but the flirtologist is here
to say the feet don't lie.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM125
label: ESTJc
text: 'T' is for touch.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM126
label: ESTJc
text:
Like humour, touch also has a positive
physiological response on our body.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM127
label: ESTJc
text:
Now as a general rule, shoulder -
it's a safe place to touch.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM128
label: ESTJc
text:
But as you go down the arm
towards the hands,

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM129
label: ESTJc
text: the touch gets more intimate.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM130
label: ESTJc
text:
That's why I recommend everyone
should kind of tap the hand

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM131
label: ESTJc
text: and say something like:

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM132
label: ESTJc
text: 'Oh, you're so funny',

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM133
label: ESTJc
text: people seem to love that stuff.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM134
label: ESTJc
text:
Oh, another place
that would be nice to touch

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM135
label: ESTJc
text: would be just here

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM136
label: ESTJc
text:
at the top of the back
between the shoulder blades,

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM137
label: ESTJc
text:
perhaps if you're passing by,
you can give a light touch.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM138
label: ESTJc
text: Now, of all of the flirting signs,

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM139
label: ESTJc
text:
people seem to be wariest
about using touch.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM140
label: ESTJc
text: As one of my clients said,

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM141
label: ESTJc
text:
'Well, the other signs
you can get away with.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM142
label: ESTJc
text:
But when it comes to touch,
you're culpable.'

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM143
label: ESTJc
text:
But touch can get you
out of the friend zone,

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM144
label: ESTJc
text:
and it can also show someone
that you're interested.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM145
label: ESTJc
text: And as long as you remember,

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM146
label: ESTJc
text: I like test cricket,

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM147
label: ESTJc
text: it lasts five days,

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM148
label: ESTJc
text:
I don't have time
to HOT-APE with everyone,

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM149
label: ESTJc
text:
then if the person
doesn't respond positively,

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM150
label: ESTJc
text: you can try someone else.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM151
label: ESTJc
text: 'A' is for attention.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM152
label: ESTJc
text: This one might seem obvious.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM153
label: ESTJc
text:
The more attention someone is paying you,
the more they like you.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM154
label: ESTJc
text:
But the problem is
once you are in the interaction,

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM155
label: ESTJc
text: it's really hard to be objective.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM156
label: ESTJc
text:
Which is why in anthropology,
we have a methodology,

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM157
label: ESTJc
text: it's called participant observation.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM158
label: ESTJc
text:
And I think this could be a really
useful tool for you to use in flirting.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM159
label: ESTJc
text:
It means that you're participating,
you're in the interaction,

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM160
label: ESTJc
text:
but you're not so in it
that you can't observe.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM161
label: ESTJc
text: So if you were to, for example,

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM162
label: ESTJc
text:
touch and say something
and see the other person blushed,

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM163
label: ESTJc
text: it means that you're not so self-conscious

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM164
label: ESTJc
text:
that you can't observe the effect
that you're having on the other person.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM165
label: ESTJc
text:
And that my friends
is when the flirting gets really fun.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM166
label: ESTJc
text: 'P' is for proximity.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM167
label: ESTJc
text: Now proximity was used in two ways.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM168
label: ESTJc
text:
The first, if you see someone
across the room

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM169
label: ESTJc
text:
and then all of a sudden
they're next to your side,

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM170
label: ESTJc
text: this is not a coincidence.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM171
label: ESTJc
text:
It means they like what they see
and they must explore further.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM172
label: ESTJc
text: The other way proximity was used

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM173
label: ESTJc
text:
is when you're actually
in the interaction,

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM174
label: ESTJc
text: they're standing closer than usual.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM175
label: ESTJc
text: So if you're attracted, great.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM176
label: ESTJc
text: If you're not, they're in your space.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM177
label: ESTJc
text:
So the last of the flirting signs
is the most important.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM178
label: ESTJc
text: Can anyone guess what it is?

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM179
label: ESTJc
text: Thank you.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM180
label: ESTJc
text: It's eye contact.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM181
label: ESTJc
text: This was the number one way

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM182
label: ESTJc
text:
that people could understand someone
who's flirting with them

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM183
label: ESTJc
text:
and the difference
between friendly and flirting.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM184
label: ESTJc
text:
So in flirting eye-contact
the gaze happened more often.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM185
label: ESTJc
text: It was held for a longer amount of time,

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM186
label: ESTJc
text: and it was more intense.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM187
label: ESTJc
text: So using these signs:

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM188
label: ESTJc
text:
humour, open body language, touch,
attention, proximity, eye contact,

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM189
label: ESTJc
text:
you can recognize
when someone is flirting with you.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM190
label: ESTJc
text:
And as a general rule,
the more signs the better.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM191
label: ESTJc
text:
Now my favourite story of HOT-APE
being used in the field

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM192
label: ESTJc
text: was relayed to me by one of my clients.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM193
label: ESTJc
text:
She had shared HOT-APE
with all of her friends.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM194
label: ESTJc
text:
And one night, they went out
HOTAPE-ing guys.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM195
label: ESTJc
text:
One of her friends was making
eye contact with a guy at the bar,

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM196
label: ESTJc
text: and she went over and spoke with him.

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM197
label: ESTJc
text: She came back a few minutes later,

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM198
label: ESTJc
text: bit dejected, my client said,

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM199
label: ESTJc
text:
'What happened? What happened?'
And she's like, 'Oh nothing.'

id: ESTJc_The Science of Flirting: Being a H.O.T. A.P.E. | Jean Smith | TEDxLSHTM200
label: ESTJc
text:
'Well, did you HOT-APE him?'
She's like, 'Yeah, yeah.'

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?0
label: INTJc
text: Hey, Vsauce. Michael here.

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?1
label: INTJc
text:
Why do humans play games?
Whether it's a video game or a board

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?2
label: INTJc
text:
game or a physical game, like soccer - or football.
I don't have to put the ball in

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?3
label: INTJc
text:
the net to survive, and, even if I did, why
would I invite a goalie and another team?

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?4
label: INTJc
text:
Games are weird. This lead Bernard Suits to
say in the 70's that a game is a voluntary

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?5
label: INTJc
text:
attempt to overcome unnecessary obstacles.
So, why do we play sports and games? How should

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?6
label: INTJc
text:
we feel about intellectualism vs. athleticism?
But, most importantly, why do Americans call

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?7
label: INTJc
text:
this game soccer while the English, and the
rest of the world, call it football?

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?8
label: INTJc
text:
It turns out that the word "soccer" doesn't
come from the United States of America. Instead,

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?9
label: INTJc
text:
the blame for the word goes to the British
themselves, specifically Oxford, where, since

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?10
label: INTJc
text:
1875, it has been popular to add the suffix
"-er" to the end of words. For example, calling

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?11
label: INTJc
text:
Radcliffe Camera the "Radder,"
or these "fivers" and "tenners."

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?12
label: INTJc
text:
We have been playing games with balls and
our feet ever since ancient times, all over

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?13
label: INTJc
text:
the world. In fact, as recently as 200 years
ago, many of these games called themselves

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?14
label: INTJc
text:
"football." A lack of standardization meant
that it was difficult to all come together

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?15
label: INTJc
text:
and agree on what you could and couldn't do
with the ball or your feet. But, luckily,

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?16
label: INTJc
text:
in 1863 the Football Association was founded
in London, England. Association football is

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?17
label: INTJc
text:
what we most commonly mean nowadays when talking
about football, or soccer. But what's the connection

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?18
label: INTJc
text:
if the Oxford "-er" was added to Association
football, shouldn't we be calling the game

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?19
label: INTJc
text:
"Association-er?" Well, let's take a closer
look at the word "association." You see what's

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?20
label: INTJc
text: hiding in there? There she is. "Soccer."

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?21
label: INTJc
text:
But we're getting ahead of ourselves because
soccer, football, is just one type of game.

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?22
label: INTJc
text:
Ultimately, what is a game? Well, one of my
favorite ways of defining "game" comes from

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?23
label: INTJc
text:
computer game designer Chris Crawford.
Let's begin with a book. This is a great book, it's

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?24
label: INTJc
text:
really fun, it's entertaining, but it's not a game.
TV shows and movies are also not games

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?25
label: INTJc
text:
because, fundamentally, they aren't interactive.
But as soon as something is both fun and

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?26
label: INTJc
text:
interactive, well, now we've got ourselves
a play-thing. There are two types of play-things,

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?27
label: INTJc
text:
according to Crawford. If you can play with
the object and it's fun but there's no goal

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?28
label: INTJc
text:
or objective associated with it, it's a toy.
If, however, there is an objective, something

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?29
label: INTJc
text:
you're supposed to accomplish, well, now you're
talking about a challenge. But there are two

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?30
label: INTJc
text:
different types of challenges. If the challenge
involves no other people or other agents,

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?31
label: INTJc
text:
it's just you, for instance, playing alone
with a Rubik's Cube, you've got yourself a

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?32
label: INTJc
text:
puzzle. If, however, there are other people
involved, well, now we've got ourselves a

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?33
label: INTJc
text: conflict.

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?34
label: INTJc
text:
In a conflict, like a foot race, you aren't
allowed to interfere with the other participants.

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?35
label: INTJc
text:
This is what Crawford calls a "competition."
If, however, you are allowed to interact with

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?36
label: INTJc
text:
and interfere with the other players and
they can do the same to you, well, in that

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?37
label: INTJc
text: case, we are talking about a full-fledged game.

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?38
label: INTJc
text:
So, a game is interactive, goal-oriented,
and involves other agents, for instance, other

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?39
label: INTJc
text:
people who can interfere with and influence
each other. Which means, technically speaking,

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?40
label: INTJc
text:
that life is a game. I mean, real life.
My life, your life, easily fit many definitions

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?41
label: INTJc
text:
of "game." And, in life, there are games that
we tend to call "sports." Now, competency

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?42
label: INTJc
text:
at sports can divide humanity into two groups.
Jocks, who are good at sports, and nerds

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?43
label: INTJc
text:
who aren't. Jocks are literally named after
the Jock Strap, which keeps your genitals

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?44
label: INTJc
text:
supported while being athletic.
But jocks are cool, right? They're fit, attractive,

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?45
label: INTJc
text:
they get invited to all the cool parties where,
in high school, they can do dangerous, cool

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?46
label: INTJc
text:
things like get drunk. And who are you if
you don't get drunk? Well, what's the word

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?47
label: INTJc
text:
"drunk" backwards? You are a "Knurd."
But that's not the origin of the word "nerd."

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?48
label: INTJc
text:
There's much debate about where the word comes
from, but what we do know is that it emerged

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?49
label: INTJc
text:
as a slang term for "lame" or "square" in
Detroit in the early 1950's.

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?50
label: INTJc
text:
The first known use of the word in print came
from Dr. Seuss himself and, fundamentally,

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?51
label: INTJc
text:
it may come from the word "nut," which meant
a crazy person, and was later altered to "nert,"

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?52
label: INTJc
text:
and, finally, "nerd." It exists today as a word
for un-athletic people largely because it

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?53
label: INTJc
text:
was popularized through its frequent use on
the US TV show "Happy Days."

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?54
label: INTJc
text:
Whether your spend your time on athletic pursuits
or intellectual pursuits, or both, games,

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?55
label: INTJc
text:
in some form, are a part of your life.
So, why do we play games?

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?56
label: INTJc
text: Humans, and many other

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?57
label: INTJc
text:
animals, play. And, perhaps, "play" originated
as a way of physically preparing our bodies

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?58
label: INTJc
text:
for life's real challenges later on. That
idea makes sense, but the evidence isn't convincing

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?59
label: INTJc
text:
because, in the wild, "play" can often lead
to a wasting of precious resources, injuries

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?60
label: INTJc
text:
and hardly comes close to simulating real
attacks and life-threatening situations.

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?61
label: INTJc
text:
The New York Times wrote a great article about
this conundrum, pointing out that physically

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?62
label: INTJc
text:
preparing the body may be less of a priority
for "play." Instead, the point of "play" might

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?63
label: INTJc
text:
be preparing the brain. Play is good for the
brain, especially during formative, juvenile

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?64
label: INTJc
text:
years, when most of us have an instinctive urge
to goof around, play and pretend anyway.

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?65
label: INTJc
text:
Young rats confined to cages with adult rats,
who refused to play with them, grew up with

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?66
label: INTJc
text:
smaller, less developed brains. This has led
to the hypothesis that games play a role in

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?67
label: INTJc
text:
the development of certain brain structures,
especially the cerebellum when we are young.

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?68
label: INTJc
text:
But, to be clear, the evidence does not show
that play is vital for the development of

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?69
label: INTJc
text:
these regions. Other methods, like exercises
or teaching, may have a similar effect.

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?70
label: INTJc
text:
They might not be as fun, but this is known
as equifinality. So there's debate as to just

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?71
label: INTJc
text:
how vital play and games really are.
Well, let's take a look at the rewards that games

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?72
label: INTJc
text: give us.

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?73
label: INTJc
text:
In the first half of the 20th century, Abraham
Maslow constructed a hierarchy of human needs.

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?74
label: INTJc
text:
The concept is popular in developmental psychology
as a way of thinking about human growth and

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?75
label: INTJc
text:
what motivates us to do things or to not
do things. In general, until the needs of

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?76
label: INTJc
text:
a lower tier are fulfilled, an individual
can't move on to fulfilling higher ones. For

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?77
label: INTJc
text:
instance, achieving confidence, or satisfying
the desire to learn and explore, aren't important

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?78
label: INTJc
text:
to a person in fear for their life and safety.
Play might be motivated by higher needs. Animals

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?79
label: INTJc
text:
play, but as we've seen in nature, not the
ones who are stressed or starving.

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?80
label: INTJc
text:
The thing is, lower needs tend to be pretty
clear cut. If I'm hungry and I eat what I

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?81
label: INTJc
text:
need, I'm done. It's not that complicated.
But, as creatures and brains and cultures

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?82
label: INTJc
text:
become more complicated, so do their needs
and the behaviors required to fulfill them.

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?83
label: INTJc
text:
This brings us back to the fact that life
itself fits Chris Crawford's definition of

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?84
label: INTJc
text:
a game. Arguably, life is the largest and
most complicated game on Earth. But playing

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?85
label: INTJc
text:
your life usually isn't as easy as simply
remembering to eat and drink and breath.

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?86
label: INTJc
text:
In life, knowing what the correct next move
is isn't always easy. Feedback is rarely immediate.

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?87
label: INTJc
text:
I don't know if the choices I made were the
best, most perfect choices for me until way

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?88
label: INTJc
text:
after I've made them, if even then.
Is this person, or city, or career right for me?

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?89
label: INTJc
text:
In life, the rules are complicated, the goals
are indeterminate and the methods for achieving

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?90
label: INTJc
text:
them are often unknown or different for every
single person. Plus, the rewards themselves

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?91
label: INTJc
text: are often slow to come or non-existent.

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?92
label: INTJc
text:
So, in the face of all of that, it's no surprise
that we invented games within the larger game

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?93
label: INTJc
text:
of life itself that ensure fast, easy-to-achieve
and understandable rewards.

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?94
label: INTJc
text:
Animals play too, but the complexity of rules
humans follow in their games, in many ways

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?95
label: INTJc
text:
reflect the complexity of the needs we find
ourselves able to pursue.

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?96
label: INTJc
text:
In life, I don't always know the right choice.
I don't know the right job to apply for.

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?97
label: INTJc
text: How to explain something to a child. How to best help my friends or when to call my mom.

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?98
label: INTJc
text:
But in Bomberman, I know exactly what every power-up
does, every time, all the time.

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?99
label: INTJc
text:
In poker, a royal flush beats two-of-a-kind,
no question about it. Couldn't be more clear.

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?100
label: INTJc
text:
But in my life, is an acquaintance or colleague
really on my side? Well, in team sports there's

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?101
label: INTJc
text: no unknown, everyone is color-coded.

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?102
label: INTJc
text:
Games and sports are a phenomenal way to feel
the rewards we need, without all of the unknowns

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?103
label: INTJc
text:
of life. Even watching games and sports, merely
being a spectator, can fulfill some of Maslow's

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?104
label: INTJc
text:
needs. I can feel a sense of belonging by
supporting a team, and by supporting a team,

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?105
label: INTJc
text: their successes can kind of become my successes.

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?106
label: INTJc
text:
What a great way to get respect without doing
a lot of work. It's known as BIRG-ing: Basking

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?107
label: INTJc
text:
In Reflected Glory. The opposite is CORF-ing:
Cutting Off Reflected Failure. If a team is

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?108
label: INTJc
text:
disgraced, I can easily say I was not really
ever that big of a fan anyway.

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?109
label: INTJc
text:
BIRG-ing and CORF-ing extend beyond sports.
We BIRG and CORF workplace projects, school

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?110
label: INTJc
text:
projects, celebrities, election candidates.
The point is, life is a game, but winning

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?111
label: INTJc
text:
and losing are nebulous. So, we invented simpler
games to provide psychological rewards faster

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?112
label: INTJc
text:
and more efficiently than life itself does.
Which is why, at their darkest, games can

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?113
label: INTJc
text: lead to procrastination or addiction.

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?114
label: INTJc
text:
But don't fear. You have the potential to
become a jock at the game of life, it's just

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?115
label: INTJc
text:
not always that fun. And whenever you play
man-made games, rest assured that it's simply

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?116
label: INTJc
text:
because you, and all of us, are able to pursue
the fulfillment of needs higher than any other

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?117
label: INTJc
text: creature on Earth.

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?118
label: INTJc
text: And as always,

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?119
label: INTJc
text: thanks for watching.

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?120
label: INTJc
text:
Oh, and if you want some soccer science, why
not check out my video with Copa90,

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?121
label: INTJc
text: where we investigate

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?122
label: INTJc
text:
whether or not it's possible to kick a football
with so much spin that it not only curves,

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?123
label: INTJc
text: but boomerangs back to the kicker.

id: INTJc_Why Do We Play Games?124
label: INTJc
text: Okay, bye.

id: ISFJc_Reference letter for graduate school: Who do you ask?0
label: ISFJc
text: Hi my name is Danine Farquharson and I'm the associate dean of Graduate Studies

id: ISFJc_Reference letter for graduate school: Who do you ask?1
label: ISFJc
text:
at Memorial University. One element of
graduate applications that students

id: ISFJc_Reference letter for graduate school: Who do you ask?2
label: ISFJc
text:
worry a lot about is the letters of
reference, so let me help. You're putting

id: ISFJc_Reference letter for graduate school: Who do you ask?3
label: ISFJc
text:
together your application packages and
have to get two maybe three letters of

id: ISFJc_Reference letter for graduate school: Who do you ask?4
label: ISFJc
text:
reference many students have the same
first question, who do I ask for a letter?

id: ISFJc_Reference letter for graduate school: Who do you ask?5
label: ISFJc
text:
The answer is, that you want to ask
professors or researchers who know your

id: ISFJc_Reference letter for graduate school: Who do you ask?6
label: ISFJc
text:
work very well. You want to ask people
who have taught you more than one class

id: ISFJc_Reference letter for graduate school: Who do you ask?7
label: ISFJc
text:
is ideal or worked with you in an
academic setting. You want to ask

id: ISFJc_Reference letter for graduate school: Who do you ask?8
label: ISFJc
text:
professors from classes in which you
have received high grades. Basically you

id: ISFJc_Reference letter for graduate school: Who do you ask?9
label: ISFJc
text:
want people who can write about your
intellectual achievement and your

id: ISFJc_Reference letter for graduate school: Who do you ask?10
label: ISFJc
text:
potential to succeed in graduate school.
The next question, is how best to ask

id: ISFJc_Reference letter for graduate school: Who do you ask?11
label: ISFJc
text:
these people. Bear in mind an important
fact here, faculty and researchers are

id: ISFJc_Reference letter for graduate school: Who do you ask?12
label: ISFJc
text:
busy people and they probably want to
help you out but you must give them lots

id: ISFJc_Reference letter for graduate school: Who do you ask?13
label: ISFJc
text:
of notice and you must be highly
organized. Make the process of writing

id: ISFJc_Reference letter for graduate school: Who do you ask?14
label: ISFJc
text:
you a strong letter easy for them, so
let's start with what not to do.

id: ISFJc_Reference letter for graduate school: Who do you ask?15
label: ISFJc
text:
Hi Danine! How are you?" Would you write
me some letters for grad school? That

id: ISFJc_Reference letter for graduate school: Who do you ask?16
label: ISFJc
text:
would be awesome because I loved your
class. Let me know. Okay? Steve. Right,

id: ISFJc_Reference letter for graduate school: Who do you ask?17
label: ISFJc
text:
please don't do that.
Believe me that email is all too common

id: ISFJc_Reference letter for graduate school: Who do you ask?18
label: ISFJc
text:
in tone and style and it will never
endear you to the person you're asking

id: ISFJc_Reference letter for graduate school: Who do you ask?19
label: ISFJc
text:
to do something for you. Put simply this
message is not professional,

id: ISFJc_Reference letter for graduate school: Who do you ask?20
label: ISFJc
text:
it lacks specifics and it results in the
professor having to ask a bunch of

id: ISFJc_Reference letter for graduate school: Who do you ask?21
label: ISFJc
text:
questions that you should have already
answered. So here's a much better way to

id: ISFJc_Reference letter for graduate school: Who do you ask?22
label: ISFJc
text:
ask, Hello Professor Farguharson, This is
Joanna Smith. I took English 3175 with

id: ISFJc_Reference letter for graduate school: Who do you ask?23
label: ISFJc
text:
you in the fall of 2016
(I earned a final grade of 85 percent). I'm

id: ISFJc_Reference letter for graduate school: Who do you ask?24
label: ISFJc
text:
writing to see if you
would be willing and able to support my

id: ISFJc_Reference letter for graduate school: Who do you ask?25
label: ISFJc
text:
graduate school applications with strong
letters of reference that attest to my

id: ISFJc_Reference letter for graduate school: Who do you ask?26
label: ISFJc
text:
academic ability and research potential
at the graduate level. I'm applying to

id: ISFJc_Reference letter for graduate school: Who do you ask?27
label: ISFJc
text:
four schools and the earliest deadline
for the letters of reference is December

id: ISFJc_Reference letter for graduate school: Who do you ask?28
label: ISFJc
text:
22 2017. If you can do this for me, I
will follow up with a detailed list of

id: ISFJc_Reference letter for graduate school: Who do you ask?29
label: ISFJc
text:
the schools and the deadlines and how to
submit each letter. I look forward to

id: ISFJc_Reference letter for graduate school: Who do you ask?30
label: ISFJc
text:
hearing from you soon,
Joanna. This one works so much better

id: ISFJc_Reference letter for graduate school: Who do you ask?31
label: ISFJc
text:
because you introduce yourself and you
give important information. Even if you

id: ISFJc_Reference letter for graduate school: Who do you ask?32
label: ISFJc
text:
know the professor really well always be
professional. This message also says how

id: ISFJc_Reference letter for graduate school: Who do you ask?33
label: ISFJc
text:
many letters you need, what the deadlines
are and the kinds of details you need

id: ISFJc_Reference letter for graduate school: Who do you ask?34
label: ISFJc
text:
included. Now the faculty member can
answer quickly with either yes I can do

id: ISFJc_Reference letter for graduate school: Who do you ask?35
label: ISFJc
text:
this for you or I am sorry I'm unable to
help. Asking for a strong letter with

id: ISFJc_Reference letter for graduate school: Who do you ask?36
label: ISFJc
text:
deadlines gives them the option of
saying no. Most professors will agree

id: ISFJc_Reference letter for graduate school: Who do you ask?37
label: ISFJc
text:
right away, but if something prevents
them from writing for you do not take it

id: ISFJc_Reference letter for graduate school: Who do you ask?38
label: ISFJc
text:
personally. You need people who will
readily agree for whatever reasons, so

id: ISFJc_Reference letter for graduate school: Who do you ask?39
label: ISFJc
text:
always have backup possibilities. When
they agree to write you need to follow

id: ISFJc_Reference letter for graduate school: Who do you ask?40
label: ISFJc
text:
up immediately with a thank you and
clear directions. The best way to give

id: ISFJc_Reference letter for graduate school: Who do you ask?41
label: ISFJc
text:
those directions is in a table like this
one. This is a tidy list with dates and

id: ISFJc_Reference letter for graduate school: Who do you ask?42
label: ISFJc
text:
how to complete the letters. This also
indicates what programs you're applying

id: ISFJc_Reference letter for graduate school: Who do you ask?43
label: ISFJc
text:
to and that's very important for letter
writers so they can tailor their letters

id: ISFJc_Reference letter for graduate school: Who do you ask?44
label: ISFJc
text:
to your applications. In your follow-up
email with this kind of table I suggest

id: ISFJc_Reference letter for graduate school: Who do you ask?45
label: ISFJc
text:
one more thing. Tell them that you will
check in four working days before each

id: ISFJc_Reference letter for graduate school: Who do you ask?46
label: ISFJc
text:
deadline, to make sure all as well and
then do it. It's okay to remind your

id: ISFJc_Reference letter for graduate school: Who do you ask?47
label: ISFJc
text:
letter writers, but do it only once.
Things can happen to delay letters but

id: ISFJc_Reference letter for graduate school: Who do you ask?48
label: ISFJc
text:
only you were in control of your
application package. You need to be the

id: ISFJc_Reference letter for graduate school: Who do you ask?49
label: ISFJc
text:
one to ensure every piece is in place by
the graduate schools deadline.

id: ISFJc_Reference letter for graduate school: Who do you ask?50
label: ISFJc
text:
So to recap. Ask early, be professional, be
precise and you'll get great letters of

id: ISFJc_Reference letter for graduate school: Who do you ask?51
label: ISFJc
text: reference.
